---
import DocsLayout from '../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
---

<DocsLayout title="Wewaran Cycles - Balinese Calendar" description="Understanding the Balinese week-based cycles">
	<h1 class="font-display text-4xl gold-accent mb-8">Wewaran Cycles</h1>

	<p class="text-lg mb-6">
		Wewaran are the various week-based cycles that operate simultaneously in the Balinese calendar system. These cycles are fundamental to understanding daily life and ceremonial timing in Bali.
	</p>

	<h2 class="font-display text-2xl text-balinese-gold mt-12 mb-6">Overview</h2>

	<p class="mb-6">
		Nine different week cycles run concurrently, each with different lengths and purposes:
	</p>

	<h2 class="font-display text-2xl text-balinese-gold mt-12 mb-6">The Nine Wewaran</h2>

	<h3 class="font-body text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Ekawara (1-day cycle)</h3>
	<p class="mb-4">The simplest cycle, repeating every day.</p>

	<h3 class="font-body text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Dwiwara (2-day cycle)</h3>
	<p class="mb-4">Alternates between two days: Menga and Pepet.</p>

	<h3 class="font-body text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Triwara (3-day cycle)</h3>
	<p class="mb-4">Three days: Pasah, Beteng, and Kajeng.</p>

	<h3 class="font-body text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Caturwara (4-day cycle)</h3>
	<p class="mb-4">Four days: Sri, Laba, Jaya, and Menala.</p>

	<h3 class="font-body text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Pancawara (5-day cycle)</h3>
	<p class="mb-4">Five days: Umanis, Paing, Pon, Wage, and Kliwon. Important for market days.</p>

	<h3 class="font-body text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Sadwara (6-day cycle)</h3>
	<p class="mb-4">Six days used for certain ceremonies and activities.</p>

	<h3 class="font-body text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Saptawara (7-day cycle)</h3>
	<p class="mb-4">Seven days: Redite, Soma, Anggara, Buda, Wraspati, Sukra, and Sabtu. Most commonly used.</p>

	<h3 class="font-body text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Astawara (8-day cycle)</h3>
	<p class="mb-4">Eight days used for specific ritual purposes.</p>

	<h3 class="font-body text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Sangawara (9-day cycle)</h3>
	<p class="mb-4">Nine days, rarely used but important for certain calculations.</p>

	<h3 class="font-body text-xl font-semibold mt-6 mb-3">Dasawara (10-day cycle)</h3>
	<p class="mb-4">Ten days used for special ceremonial purposes and divination.</p>

	<h2 class="font-display text-2xl text-balinese-gold mt-12 mb-6">Working with Wewaran in Code</h2>

	<div class="code-block mb-6">
		<pre><code class="language-rust">use balinese_calendar::BalineseDate;

let date = BalineseDate::from_ymd(2023, 1, 1)?;

// Access different week cycles
println!("Saptawara: {}", date.saptawara());
println!("Pancawara: {}", date.pancawara());
println!("Triwara: {}", date.triwara());
println!("Dwiwara: {}", date.dwiwara());</code></pre>
	</div>

	<h2 class="font-display text-2xl text-balinese-gold mt-12 mb-6">Significance</h2>

	<p class="mb-6">
		The combination of all nine Wewaran creates a complex system for determining:
	</p>

	<ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 mb-8">
		<li>Auspicious and inauspicious days</li>
		<li>Market days and trading schedules</li>
		<li>Ceremonial occasions</li>
		<li>Daily activities and work</li>
	</ul>

